<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910830-0045</DOCNO><DOCID>910830-0045.</DOCID><HL>   Northwest Airlines Orders   Four Planes From Airbus</HL><DATE>08/30/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3</SO><CO>   BA E.CSA F.ABI F.ASP F.CFM F.SNM G.DAI G.MES GE NWA U.BA</CO><MS>CONGLOMERATES (CGL)CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)AEROSPACE (ARO)AUTOMOBILES (AUT)CONGLOMERATES (CGL)</IN><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)EUROPE (EU)FRANCE (FR)GERMANY (GE)MINNESOTA (MN)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)SPAIN (SP)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   ST. PAUL, Minn. -- Northwest Airlines said it is buyingfour Airbus Industrie A-340 aircraft and taking options on anadditional six A-340s in a transaction it valued at $1.4billion.   The unit of NWA Inc. said it is also taking options on twoadditional Boeing Co. 747-400 aircraft in a pact valued at$340 million.</LP><TEXT>   The Airbus orders and options aren't consideredparticularly large but represent a plus for the Europeanaircraft consortium. Northwest said the A-340 planesrepresent &quot;a good long-term fit with our future route plans.&quot;   Northwest said it plans to use the A340s and 747-400s forits lucrative trans-Pacific business, and said the decisionsare part of an effort to modernize its fleet. Northwest saidit will be the first airline to use the A-340 ontrans-Pacific routes.   Northwest already operates 747-400s, which seat 404passengers. The new A-340s, which will seat 251 passengers,will be in addition to orders and options placed earlier.   Northwest said it will receive its first A-340 in early1993, and take delivery of more 747-400s that year, as well.   With the additional planes, Northwest said its fleet willinclude 30 A-340s and 12 747-400s on order and option. Itsfleet includes 248 planes on order and option.   Meanwhile, CFM International said it received an order topower Northwest's A-340 aircraft with its CFM-56-5C engines.The order is valued at $275 million. CFM International is ajoint venture of General Electric Co., Fairfield, Conn., andSnecma of France.</TEXT></DOC>